ce:section.ce:para:
Elemental analysis was measured by energy-dispersive X-ray (EDX) spectroscopy (Table 1
                        ). The result revealed that MR-CDs are composed of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen elements. The analysis indicates that reaction time has no significant impact on the elemental concentration of carbon and oxygen, except for AG30 CDs, which showed a slight increase in oxygen content. This is due to the minor time difference implemented in this study, where we intentionally avoid the total carbonization of the sample to achieve our aim of producing edible/biocompatible MR-CDs. However, the nitrogen content decreased with increased reaction time from 28% in AG15 to 24% in Arg30. This is an expected result, as increasing reaction time results in protein degradation and nitrogen loss. The same observation was reported in food-based CDs MR-CDs (Song et al., 2019). The results showed relative homogeneity in the chemical composition of our CDs produced at increasing reaction time. The elemental analysis further correlates with the FTIR results. Fig. 3
                         shows the FTIR spectrums of the three MR-CDs. The broad band at 3358 cm−1 in all three samples could be attributed to the stretching vibrations of the OH and NH2 groups, accounting for the solubility and stability of the CDs in aqueous solutions. The band at 1557 cm−1 is assigned to aromatic C=C vibrations (Sevilla & Fuertes, 2009). The three characteristic bands observed at 1349 cm-1, 1455 cm−1, and 1690 cm−1 indicate the presence of C−N, N-H and C=O, which are specific markers of tertiary, secondary, and primary amides, respectively. Amides are known to be major constituents of MR products (Hayase et al., 1985). The bands around 1690 cm−1 are attributed to the C=O vibration of the carboxyl group; the intensity of this particular band is noticeably higher in the CDs of AG30, which may indicate a higher concentration of the carboxyl group with increasing heating time. Other bands at 1114, 1398, and 1454 cm−1 may correspond to C-O-C, CH or CH2, and CH3, respectively. According to the results, MR-CDs surfaces are rich in hydroxyl, amino, and carbonyl groups. Indeed, the presence of the formerly mentioned functional groups on the surface of MR-CDs is noteworthy, as they are known to facilitate cell uptake and promote interactions with immune cells (Yan et al., 2018). Thus, MR-CDs could potentially serve as biocompatible nanostructures with favorable surface properties for cellular applications. Additionally, the presence of amides further characterizes the molecular composition of the MR-CDs (Ren et al., 2019).
